1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nf3 Nd7 7. h4 h6 8. h5 Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Qb6 { This is the first time I've seen Qb6 - up to here, everything has been part of my theory. Regardless, I found the best move. } 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd5 15. Kb1 (15. c4 { I avoided the immediate c4, thinking that would only bring his knight closer to my king. But it allows Qd7+ and I underestimated that my attack hits first. } 15... Nb4 16. Bxb4 Bxb4 17. Qd7+ Kf8 18. Ne4) 15... O-O-O (15... Qxf2 16. Ne4 { I had only seen this far, but after Qf5 the following line is strong for white as the black king is still in the center. } 16... Qf5 17. c4 Nb6) 16. Qf3 (16. c4 Nb4 17. Qf3) 16... Bb4 17. Qxf7 { Seeing as I've been playing Yasser's opening, I decided to follow through and pawn grab because I saw that Qxe6 comes with check and might allow me to play Qd6+ swapping queens in some lines. Unfortunately, I should have feared the attack a bit more. } (17. c3 Ba3 18. Bc1 Bc5 19. Ne4 Rhf8) 17... Bxd2 18. Qxe6+ Kb8 19. Rxd2 Nc3+ 20. Kc1 (20. Ka1 Rxd2 21. bxc3 Rhd8) 20... Rxd2 21. Kxd2 Qd4+ 22. Kc1 Qf4# 0-1


