1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6!? { I foolishly thought that this move would mean we would transition into a Najdorf. However, it was instead used to avoid the more testing Kalashnikov variations. } 3. d4?! cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 { Nb5 is the usual response here. } (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 { Mainline Najdorf }) 5. Nf3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Nc3 h6 8. h3 { [%cal Gf6g4] } (8. Bc4 Ng4 { I felt I would be immediately worse if I allowed Ng4 to hit here. But playing the slow h3 felt like a concession, so I immediately began contemplating how to use it to launch a kingside attack. }) 8... Be6 9. Be2 Nc6 10. Qd2 Qa5!? { Objectively, probably not best. But stopping me from castling queenside should be seen as an achievement. The queen also supports a d5 break. } { [%cal Ge6a2,Gf8a3,Gf6e4,Gc6b4,Gc6d4,Ga5c3,Ga5a2] } 11. Rd1 (11. O-O-O b5 { Black's attack is way too fast. }) 11... Be7 { I refused to castle kingside - envisioning a scenario where we are castled on the same side of the board, black gets in d5, and has active pieces aimed at my queenside. But by avoiding any committal king move, black still has the option to go queenside with the king. } 12. g4?! (12. a3!? O-O 13. g4 { This would have been a better version of the game for white. I have a clear target with g5 coming. But black does not have to commit to castling kingside even here... }) 12... O-O-O 13. a3 d5! { With d5 finally on board, black has now equalized. } 14. Nxd5 Qxd2+ 15. Rxd2 Nxd5 16. exd5 Bxd5 17. O-O (17. Bb6 Rd7 18. O-O?? Bxf3 { A line I wanted to avoid - so I kept the bishop on e3 to protect my rook. }) 17... h5! 18. Rfd1! { Neither side wants to give ground on the kingside. Playing g5 weakens h3. Playing gxh5 activates black's rook. } 18... Be6 19. Ng5! { Keeping the pawn on g4 and attempting to win the bishop pair! } 19... Bxg5 20. Bxg5 f6 21. Be3 hxg4 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 (22... Nxd8!? { The alternative keeps more pieces on the board and might give white a little more play. } 23. hxg4 Rh4 24. Kg2!! Bxg4 25. Rh1 { White is better in this stellar line. }) 23. Rxd8+ Kxd8 24. hxg4 { Keeping the bishop pair is crucial in this endgame. White's mobility with the bishop pair is his greatest asset. With black's central control and good knight though, we still have an even position. } 24... Kd7 25. Kg2 Kd6 26. f4 { I realized that if I didn't play f4 right now, I was simply going to be stuck with a target kingside pawn chain. By liquidating the kingside, I was hoping to eventually be able to activate my queenside majority... but subconsciously I was already thinking that a draw would be a relief. } 26... Bd5+ (26... e4 27. f5 Bd5 28. Bf4+) 27. Kg3 Na5 28. b3 { Controlling the c4 square and stopping Bc4 (robbing me of the bishop pair) } 28... Be4 29. Bd1 { Passive, but solid. } (29. b4! Nc6 30. Bc5+ Kd5 31. c4+ Ke6 { The line that Ashritha said she missed before playing Be4. But white missed it too... }) 29... b5 30. Bb6 Nc6 31. c3 { Stops the knight from getting to the juicy b4 or d4 squares. } 31... Ne7 32. a4 { Running low on time, I completely missed that Nd5 was coming. At this point, I felt that I was barely hanging on (both on the clock and on the board) } 32... Nd5 { [%csl Gf4,Gc3,Gb6] } 33. fxe5+! { Thankfully I have this move which gives black a passed pawn, but ruins the kingside structure. } 33... fxe5 (33... Kxe5?! 34. Bd4+) 34. Ba5 bxa4 35. bxa4 Kc5 36. Bb3! { Prevents the king from entering via the light squares. I didn't realize this with so little time on my clock, but it also threatens to go into an opposite-color bishop endgame. } { [%csl Gb4,Gc4,Gd4] } 36... Bd3 37. Kf3?? { I flagged right around here, but my idea to get to the queenside via f3 was completely flawed. } (37. Bxd5! Kxd5 38. Bc7 { The opposite color bishop ending should be drawn, but a few more precise moves are required to avoid being a pawn down. } 38... e4 39. Kf4 Kc4 40. Be5 g5+ 41. Ke3 Kb3 42. Bf6) 37... e4+! (37... Bc4 38. Bc2 { The line I was hoping for. I felt that I could draw this position. }) 38. Kf2 e3+ { I flagged here, but it's clear that black's passed pawn is pushing through. The king is not able to blockade it on e1. } 39. Ke1 Nf4 40. Bb4+ Kc6 { Ng2 is unstoppable, and the queening square is under black's control. } *


