1. e4 e6 2. d4 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 2... d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4 c5 6. Ngf3 Nc6 { [%clk 0:03:04] } 7. dxc5?! (7. c3 { What I was expecting, with the normal French fight over the center. }) 7... Bxc5 8. Nb3 { [%clk 0:03:04] } 8... Be7 { [%clk 0:03:01] } (8... Bb6 9. Bd3 f6 { The only way the engine shows leads to an advantage for black. }) 9. Be3 O-O 10. Bd3 f6 11. exf6 Nxf6 { [%clk 0:02:49] } 12. O-O Nb4?! 13. c3 (13. Be2 b6 14. c3 Nc6 15. Bd3 { I was unsure how I was making progress if white kept his strong bishop. }) 13... Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Ne4 15. Rae1 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 15... Qc7 16. Nbd2 Nc5 17. Qe2 a5 (17... b6!? { Threatens Ba6 one move faster and asks white more questions. } { [%cal Gc8a6] } 18. b4!? $13) 18. Nb3 Nxb3 (18... b6 19. Nxc5 bxc5! { For some reason I missed the fact that I can recapture with the b pawn - keeping the good, dark-squared bishop on the board. }) 19. axb3 b6 20. Nd4 Bd7 21. Qg4 Qd6 (21... e5?? 22. Ne6 Bxe6 23. Qxe6+ Kh8 24. fxe5 $18) 22. h3 Rae8 23. Kh1 Bd8 24. Qg3 Bc7 25. Nf3!! { I only saw Nf3 as a way to reposition the knight to the strong e5 square. Thus, I prepared Be8 in order to hold on. However, it also vacates the d4 square for the bishop to enter the attack, with potentially more threats than a strong knight on e5. } 25... Rc8? 26. Bd4! Qe7 27. Be5 { [%clk 0:00:48] } 27... Bd6 28. Bxd6 Qxd6 29. Nd4 Rce8 { Now we've entered a good knight vs bad bishop endgame and white can only be the one who's better. } 30. Kg1 g6? 31. Re5 Kg7 32. h4! { Already I could see the end in sight. White's attack is too strong, and I only had 20 seconds left. } 32... Rf5 (32... Rf6 33. h5 Ref8 34. hxg6 Rxg6 35. Qe1 Rg8) 33. Nxf5+ exf5 34. Rxe8 Bxe8 35. Qe3 { [%clk 0:00:36] } 35... Bc6 36. Re1 Qf6 37. Qe7+ Qxe7 38. Rxe7+ Kh6 39. Re6 Bb5 40. Rxb6 Bd3 41. b4 axb4 42. cxb4 Bc4 43. Rc6 Bd3 (43... Kh5 44. Rxc4 dxc4 45. b5 $18) 44. Rc5 Kh5 45. g3 Be2 46. Kf2 Bc4 47. b5 Bxb5 48. Rxb5 Kg4 49. Rxd5 h6 50. b4 g5 51. hxg5 { 1-0 White wins. } { [%clk 0:00:52] } 1-0


