1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Qc2 d6 (4... O-O 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 7. Bg5 Ba6 8. e3 d6 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Ne2 h6 11. Bh4 c5 12. O-O Rc8) 5. e4 Bxc3+ (5... c5!?) 6. bxc3 e5 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 b6 9. O-O Nc6 10. Rb1 Ba6 11. f4 Re8?! { It doesn't appear immediately, but allowing Bg5 leads to an impossible pin... } (11... h6!? { To avoid the possible bishop pin after fxe5. } 12. d5 Na5 $10) 12. fxe5 dxe5 13. d5 Na5 14. Bg5! { Gives up a pawn, but white has a ferocious kingside attack. } 14... Bxc4 15. Ng3 Qd6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Nf5 Qc5+ 18. Kh1 Bxd3?! (18... Kh8!? { A better version than the game. There's no reason to help out his queen getting closer to my kingside. And if he ever takes my bishop, this just helps out my knight getting back into the game too. }) 19. Qxd3 Kh8 20. Nh6 Qe7 21. Qh3 Nc4 22. Rf5 Rg8 { The computer agrees - the best move at this point is giving up the exchange. } 23. Nxg8 Rxg8 24. Rbf1 Rg6 25. Rh5 Rg7 26. Rf3 Nd6 27. Rg3 Rxg3 (27... Qf8 { The only move to prolong the inevitable. } 28. Qh4 { [%csl Gf6] } 28... Ne8 29. Rh3 Qg8 { This is clearly resignable, but amazingly there's no immediate breakthrough. }) 28. Rxh7+ Kg8 29. Rh8+ Kg7 30. Qh6# { 1-0 White wins by checkmate. } 1-0


