5?? { [%cal Ga5c4] [%clk 0:00:19] } (17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 21. Rxc8 Qxc8 22. Qxd5 Rxe5! { [%cal Gc8c1,Gc1f4,Gf4c1] }) 18. Bxf6 { [%clk 0:01:52] } 18... Bxf6 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 19. Qh5?? { Another blunder! } { [%clk 0:01:31] } (19. Bxh7+ Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Qxf7+ Kh8 $10 { Amazingly, this is just a drawn position. I'm sure white would play on here with Ne2 or something, but black can apparently hold with perfect play. } 22. Ne4 (22. Ne2!? Bxe5! 23. Rxc8 Bxc8 24. dxe5 Rxe5 $19) 22... dxe4 23. Rxc8 Bxc8 $10 { [%cal Gf7h5,Gh5f7] }) 19... g6 { The only move at this point that doesn't immediately lose. Amazingly, black has now bought himself enough time to handle white's initiative. } { [%clk 0:00:23] } 20. Qf3 { [%cal Gc6a5] [%clk 0:00:23] } 20... Nc4 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 21. Re2?? { White simply missed that black had enough attackers on e5. This last blunder proves to be enough for black to enter into a much better endgame. } { [%clk 0:00:18] } (21. Nxc4 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1 bxc4 $17 { White has a backward pawn on b2 that will next be targeted. Black's king is perfectly safe after Bg7. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gb7c6,Gc8b8,Gd8b6] }) 21... Nxe5 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 22. dxe5 { [%clk 0:00:29] } 22... Rxe5 { Taking with the rook encourages more trades. } { [%clk 0:00:31] } 23. Rxe5 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 23... Bxe5 { [%clk 0:00:43] } 24. Rd1 { [%clk 0:00:36] } 24... Qf6! { The move I'm most proud of. More trades! } { [%clk 0:00:29] } 25. Qxf6 { [%clk 0:00:16] } (25. Nxd5 Qxf3 { [%csl Gf3][%cal Gg8f8] } 26. gxf3 (26. Ne7+?? Kf8 $19) 26... Bxd5 27. Rxd5 Rc1+ 28. Kg2 Bxb2 $19 { White's most active try transitions into a hopelessly lost endgame. } { [%csl Gf2,Gf3,Gh3] }) 25... Bxf6 { [%clk 0:00:41] } 26. Rd3 { [%clk 0:00:15] } (26. Nxd5?? Bxd5 27. Rxd5 Rc1+ 28. Kh2 Rxb1 $19) 26... d4 { Black's one extra pawn pushes and converts from a static weakness to a dynamic powerhouse. } { [%clk 0:00:39] } 27. Ne2 { [%clk 0:00:24] } 27... Be4 { [%clk 0:00:22] } 28. Rd1 { [%clk 0:00:35] } 28... Bxb1 { [%clk 0:00:29] } 29. Rxb1 { [%clk 0:00:45] } 29... d3 { [%clk 0:00:39] } 30. Nc1 { [%clk 0:00:34] } 30... d2 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 31. Nb3 { Obviously black is winning in this situation. Regardless, I couldn't find a clean way through during the game, so I traded my d pawn for two passed pawns. } { [%clk 0:00:44] } 31... Rd8 { [%cal Gd2d1] [%clk 0:00:21] } (31... Bg5! { The move I missed. } 32. Rd1 (32. h4 Rc1+!) 32... Rc1! { In every variation, black is winning a piece and therefore the game. }) 32. Rd1 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 32... Bxb2 { [%cal Gb2c3] [%clk 0:00:27] } 33. Rxd2 { [%clk 0:00:34] } 33... Rxd2 { [%clk 0:00:36] } 34. Nxd2 { [%clk 0:00:46] } 34... Bxa3 { Now it becomes a matter of technique. From here on out, I did my utmost to ensure that white's knight never got any sort of activity. I had recently viewed the Fischer-Taimonov 6-0 series, and was thinking how this was simply a much improved position of game 4. } { [%clk 0:00:47] } 35. Kf1 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 35... a5 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 36. Ke2 { [%clk 0:01:04] } 36... Kf8 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 37. Kd3 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 37... Bc5 { No king activity. } { [%clk 0:00:44] } 38. Nb3 { [%clk 0:01:01] } 38... Bb6 { No knight activity. } { [%csl Gb3,Gb6][%cal Gb3d4,Gb3c5,Gb3a5] [%clk 0:00:53] } 39. f3 { [%clk 0:01:09] } 39... Ke7 { [%clk 0:01:00] } 40. Nd2 { [%clk 0:01:17] } 40... f5 { [%cal Gd2e4] [%clk 0:01:09] } 41. Nb1 { [%clk 0:01:11] } 41... Kd6 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 42. Nc3 { [%clk 0:01:10] } 42... Kc6 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 43. Ne2 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 43... a4 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 44. h4 { [%clk 0:01:21] } 44... Bf2 { [%clk 0:00:47] } 45. h5! { The only move worth trying. I didn't feel like taking that pawn and ruining my structure. Instead, I preferred to keep everything 100% under control by playing g5. Unfortunately, this allows white to fix all my pawns on dark squares... but it's no matter as I'm completely winning, regardless. } { [%clk 0:01:23] } 45... g5 { [%clk 0:00:38] } 46. g4 { [%clk 0:0