1. e4 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 1... c5 { [%clk 0:02:51] } 2. Nf3 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 2... e6 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 3. d4 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 3... cxd4 { [%clk 0:02:51] } 4. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 4... Nc6 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 5. Nb5!? { [%cal Gb5d6] [%clk 0:02:59] } 5... d6 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 6. c4 { I really like the Maroczy bind from both sides. So I'm willing to break opening principles (like: don't move the same piece a million times in the opening) if the variation leads to positions I like. } { [%clk 0:02:56] } 6... a6 { [%clk 0:02:46] } 7. N5c3 { [%clk 0:02:57] } 7... Nf6 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 8. Be2 { [%clk 0:02:47] } 8... Qc7 { [%clk 0:02:36] } (8... Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Be3 b6 11. Na3 Bb7 12. Qd2 (12. Qb3!? { [%cal Gb3b6,Ge3b6] } 12... Nd7 13. Rfd1 Nc5 14. Qc2) 12... Ne5 13. f3 Qc7 14. Rac1 Rac8 15. Rfd1 { The normal move order to reach the game position on move 15. }) 9. O-O { [%clk 0:02:19] } 9... Be7 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 10. Be3 { [%clk 0:02:07] } 10... b6 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 11. Na3 { [%clk 0:01:58] } (11. Nd2! Bb7 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Nd5!! $16 { An improvement for white that shows why the default move order is better for black. }) (11. Qb3!? Nd7 12. Rd1 Nc5 13. Qc2 Bb7 14. a3 { Also interesting - again showcasing why the knight is more flexible on b1 than a3 } { [%cal Gb2b4] }) 11... Bb7 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 12. Qd2 { [%clk 0:01:46] } 12... O-O { [%clk 0:02:29] } 13. Rac1 { [%clk 0:01:39] } 13... Ne5 { [%clk 0:02:28] } 14. f3 { [%clk 0:01:37] } 14... Rac8 { [%clk 0:02:29] } 15. Rfd1 { We've transposed to one of the mainlines in this variation, although I wasn't completely aware of it at the time. As always, the knight on a3 is the problem piece. However, at the moment it's defending the important c4 pawn, so there is no need for b3 - there's no real pressure down the open c file. } { [%clk 0:01:30] } 15... h5 { The start of the classic checkmating idea of h5-h4-h3 to loosen up the king. h3 weakens the important g3 and f4 squares, so I figured it was better to instead keep everything defended with the pawn on h3. g3 will be the necessary response to keep the squares under control. } { [%clk 0:02:26] } 16. Kh1?! { The king is not safer on h1 than g1. I end up finding this out later in the game. } { [%clk 0:01:20] } (16. Na4! { [%cal Ga4b6,Ge3b6] } 16... Nfd7 17. b4 { A clear improvement from the game. Now h4 can be met with f4. } 17... h4?! 18. f4 Ng6 19. Bf3 h3 20. g3 $14) 16... h4 { [%clk 0:02:18] } 17. Na4 { The right idea, but one move later than it should have happened. } { [%clk 0:01:17] } 17... Ned7? { However, my GM opponent misses the more forcing variation. } { [%clk 0:02:16] } (17... h3! 18. Bxb6 Qc6! $17 { [%cal Gc6a4,Gh3g2] }) 18. b4 { [%clk 0:00:54] } 18... h3 { [%clk 0:02:03] } 19. g3 { [%clk 0:00:42] } 19... Qb8 { [%clk 0:01:43] } (19... Bxe4!! 20. fxe4 Nxe4 21. Qe1 Qc6 $19 { The loose piece on a4 comes to bite me. } { [%cal Gc6h1,Gc6a4] }) 20. Bf1?? { The actual "human" mistake of the game. I miscalculated a crucial idea black has, and this ensures black's attack goes through. } { [%clk 0:00:42] } (20. Nxb6?? Nxb6 21. Bxb6 Nxe4 $19 { [%cal Gb8b6,Gb7e4] }) (20. Kg1 { It's crucial to get off the long diagonal as the following tactic shows. Already we can see why Kh1 earlier in this game was weak. }) 20... Ne5! { [%clk 0:01:39] } 21. Be2 { Necessary. But already, white is in severe trouble. } { [%clk 0:00:13] } (21. Qf2?? Nxf3 22. Qxf3 Bxe4 { I had been planning Qf2 to defend everything, but the king and queen alignment instantly ends the game. }) 21... d5 { [%clk 0:01:26] } 22. cxd5 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 22... exd5 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 23. Nxb6 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 23... dxe4 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 24. f4 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 24... Rxc1 { [%clk 0:01:24] } (24... Nf3?? 25. Nxc8! Nxd2? 26. Nxe7+ Kh7 27. Rxd2 { A beautiful queen sacrifice fully saves the position for white. }) 25. Qxc1! { Getting out of Nf3 ideas with tempo. } { [%clk 0:00:06] } 25... Nf3 { [%clk 0:01:22] } 26. Nd7! { Trades are crucial at this junction. Otherwise, the white king gets torn apart. } { [%clk 0:00:06] } 26... Ng4?? { Aman said "he has 5 seconds left on his clock in this 3+2 game. So rather than play practically, let's go for a crazy mate and see if we can't flag him. } { [%clk 0:00:15] } (26... Nxd7 27. Rxd7 Rc8?? (27... Bxb4 28. Nc4 { Here, black still holds an edge. But in this complicated position, it's entirely possible for it to go either way. }) 28. Bc4! Bxb4 29. Bxf7+ Kf8 30. Bc4!! { White is back in the game with his own threats against black's king. } { [%cal Gc1b2,Gb2g7,Gc1a3,Ga3f8] }) 27. Nxb8 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 27... Rc8 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 28. Qxc8+ { [%clk 0:00:04] } 28... Bxc8 { [%clk 0:00:17] } 29. Bg1 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 29... Bb7 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 30. Rd7 { I flagged as I played Rd7. It was clear to me that I was winning, but I don't think I could convert this with only 2 seconds per move, even up a rook and piece. The game likely would have continued: } 30... Bxb4 31. Nc2 Bc5 32. Bxc5 e3 { [%cal Gb7h1] } 33. Bxe3 { with a clearly winning position but no direct win in sight. } (33. Rxb7?? Nf2#) *


