58] } 16... Qd8 { [%clk 0:02:38] } 17. Qe3 { [%clk 0:01:54] } 17... Qb6 { [%clk 0:02:23] } 18. Qg3 { [%clk 0:01:42] } (18. Qxb6 Nxb6 19. Bf3 { Trading queens is fine for white too, but there are still hopes of a kingside attack. }) (18. Qh3! { Further pressuring f5 is even better. } { [%cal Gh3e6] }) 18... Nf6 { [%clk 0:02:07] } 19. Be3 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 19... Qc6 { [%clk 0:01:55] } 20. exf5 { [%clk 0:01:22] } 20... Bxf5 { [%clk 0:01:53] } 21. Bf3 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 21... Qd7 { [%clk 0:01:52] } 22. Bd4?! { [%clk 0:01:15] } (22. Na4! { Missed. This move wins the exchange by force: Nb6 is unavoidable. } { [%cal Ga4b6,Ge3b6] }) 22... Ne8?? { [%clk 0:01:50] } (22... Rf8 23. Rcd1 { White remains in the driver seat. }) 23. Bxg7 { [%clk 0:01:15] } 23... Nxg7 { Now that the dark squared bishops have been exchanged, it's clear that kingside pressure in combination with pressure on the backward/potentially backward d/e pawns gives white a winning position. } { [%clk 0:01:52] } 24. Nd5 { [%cal Gd5b6] [%clk 0:00:53] } 24... Qd8 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 25. Qg5 { [%csl Ge7] [%clk 0:00:44] } (25. Rce1?! e6! { My knight gets kicked back and I don't quite see a clean way forward again. }) 25... Kf7 { [%clk 0:01:26] } (25... e6?? 26. Ne7+ Kf7 27. Nxc8 $18) 26. Rce1 { [%clk 0:00:28] } (26. g4 { I wanted to commit to this move only after putting my rook on the e file... } 26... Be6 27. f5! { The follow-up move I missed though. White crashes through on the kingside immediately. }) 26... e6! { [%clk 0:01:27] } 27. Qxd8 { [%clk 0:00:18] } (27. Qh6!? { I knew there were knight sacrifices around here, but I didn't see what to do next if black didn't take the knight... } 27... exd5 28. Bxd5+ Ne6 29. Qxh7+ $18) (27. g4! { The engine recommendation. Black cannot handle the threats, even with the queens off the board: } 27... Qxg5 28. fxg5 { [%cal Gf1f7] } 28... exd5 29. Bxd5+ $18 { [%cal Gf1f7] } 29... Kf8 30. gxf5 Nxf5 { [%cal Gd5b7,Gd5e6] }) 27... Rxd8 { [%clk 0:01:29] } 28. Nb6 { [%clk 0:00:19] } 28... Rab8 { My knight is better than either black rook. I'm in essence already up the exchange. } { [%clk 0:01:28] } 29. g4! { [%clk 0:00:15] } 29... Bd3 { [%clk 0:01:29] } 30. Rf2 { Threatening to trap the wayward d3 bishop... } { [%cal Gf2d2] [%clk 0:00:17] } 30... g5?? { [%clk 0:01:17] } (30... d5! { A better version of the game! } 31. cxd5 exd5 32. Bxd5+ Kf8 $16 { White remains better, but there's not such a crushing bind as in the game. }) 31. Rd2 { [%clk 0:00:16] } 31... Bg6 { [%clk 0:01:16] } 32. fxg5 { Not only am I up a pawn, but my kingside majority should be yielding a new queen soon, and I still retain all my pressure on the central pawns. I knew I was completely winning in the game. But I had mere seconds left to convert... } { [%clk 0:00:17] } 32... e5 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 33. h4 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 33... Kg8 { [%clk 0:00:28] } 34. Rf2 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 34... Bf7 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 35. Bd5 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 35... Be6 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 36. Kg2 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 36... Bxd5+ { [%clk 0:00:11] } 37. Nxd5 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 37... Ne6 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 38. Rf6 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 38... Nd4 { [%cal Gd5b6] [%clk 0:00:12] } 39. Kg3 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 39... b5 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 40. Ref1 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 40... bxc4 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 41. bxc4 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 41... Rb7 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 42. R1f2 { Honestly the first move that was purely down to time pressure. I couldn't visualize the board clearly with so little time. In retrospect, pushing the h pawn first is just a better version of the game. } { [%clk 0:00:06] } 42... Kg7 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 43. h5 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 43... Nc6 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 44. h6+ { [%clk 0:00:08] } 44... Kg8 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 45. g6! { I'm particularly proud of this move. Now I have two connected passed pawns that are also supporting the kingside assault. } { [%clk 0:00:09] } 45... hxg6 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 46. Rxg6+ { [%clk 0:00:11] } 46... Kh7 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 47. Rgf6 { [%clk 0:00:09] } (47. Rff6!? { Possibly more precise. Now the threat of Rg7+ prevents black from leaving the 7th rank with one rook. }) 47... Nd4 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 48. Kh4 { [%clk 0:00:09] } (48. g5 { More to the point. I was somehow worried about knight checks? }) 48... Rb1 { [%cal Gf6f7,Gh7h6] [%clk 0:00:06] } 49. g5?? { [%clk 0:00:10] } (49. Ne7 { Forced mate? It was not clear to me at all why this would be good for me. I'd much rather play Nf6+. The threat though is: } 49... a5 (49... Rg8 50. Nxg8 Kxg8 51. Kg5 $18 { [%cal Gg5g6,Gf6f8] }) 50. Rf7+! Kxh6 (50... Kh8 51. Ng6+ Kg8 52. Rg7#) 51. g5#) (49. Rf7+ { A clean way forward: } 49... Kxh6?? (49... Kg6 50. R2f6#) (49... Kg8 50. Ne7+ Kh8 51. Ng6+ Kg8 52. h7#) (49... Kh8 50. g5 Rh1+ 51. Kg4 Rg1+ 52. Kh5 Rh1+ 53. Kg6 Rg8+ 54. Rg7 Rxg7+ 55. hxg7+ Kg8 56. Ne7#) 50. R2f6#) 49... Rh1+! { [%clk 0:00:08] } 50. Kg4 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 50... Rg1+ { [%clk 0:00:09] } 51. Kh4 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 51... Rh1+ { [%clk 0:00:11] } 52. Kg3 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 52... Rg1+?? { This move allows me to perform the classic Lucena bridge technique in order to block further checks along the g file. White is once again winning. } { [%clk 0:00:11] } (52... Rg8!! { Unbelievably, it's impossible to defend the g pawn. Black will win both the kingside pawns and equalize the game. } { [%cal Gg8g5] }) 53. Rg2 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 53... Rh1 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 54. Rf7+ { [%clk 0:00:11] } 54... Kg6 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 55. Rg7+ { [%clk 0:00:09] } 55... Kf5 { "Are you kidding me there's no mate?" } { [%clk 0:00:04] } 56. Rf2+ { [%clk 0:00:04] } 56... Ke4 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 57. Nf6+ { [%clk 0:00:05] } 57... Ke3 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 58. h7 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 58... Rg1+ { [%clk 0:00:06] } 59. Kh2 { [%clk 0:00:05] } (59. Rg2 { Obviously better than what I played in the game. Black has some annoying moves here, but these pawns are too strong: } 59... Nf5+ 60. Kg4 Rxg2+ (60... Nxg7 61. Rxg1 { g6 and Kg5 are coming to infiltrate... }) 61. Kxf5 Rh2?? (61... Rh8 62. g6 $18 { [%cal Gg7g8] }) 62. Ng4+ $18 { [%cal Gg4e3,Gg4h2] }) 59... Kxf2 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 60. Ne4+ { [%clk 0:00:06] } 60... Kf1 { [%clk 0:00:07] } 61. Nd2+ { [%clk 0:00:06] } (61. Rf7+ { The move I missed with 3 seconds on my clock... } 61... Ke1 62. Kxg1 { White regains the rook and ensures a quick victory. }) 61... Kf2 { I saw the perpetual, but I figured I had even more with these killer pawns. } { [%cal Gd2e4] [%clk 0:00:07] } 62. Rg8?? { [%clk 0:00:07] } 62... Rg2+ { [%clk 0:00:04] } 63. Kh3 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 63... Rg3+ { [%clk 0:00:06] } 64. Kh4?? { [%clk 0:00:08] } (64. Kh2 $10 { Maintains the draw. Black has nothing more than a perpetual as well. Indeed these pawns are too strong. }) 64... Nf5+! { [%clk 0:00:08] } 65. Kh5 { [%clk 0:00:09] } 65... Rh3+ { [%clk 0:00:09] } 66. Kg6 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 66... Ne7+ { [%clk 0:00:11] } 67. Kg7 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 67... Rxh7+!! { The key idea that ensures black is not just equal, but completely winning! } { [%clk 0:00:11] } 68. Kxh7 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 68... Rxg8 { I could have resigned here, but I played a few more moves on momentum until I saw the clock situation and had a moment to take in just how royally I screwed up my position. } { [%clk 0:00:13] } 69. Ne4+ { [%clk 0:00:11] } 69... Kf3 { [%clk 0:00:13] } 70. Nxd6 { [%clk 0:00:11] } 70... Rxg5 { [%clk 0:00:14] } 71. c5 { [%clk 0:00:10] } 71... Nc6 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 72. Kh6 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 72... Rg1 { [%clk 0:00:15] } 73. Kh5 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 73... Nb4 { 0-1 White resigns. } { I'm extremely proud of my play this game. In particular, I kept more tension in the position than I normally do (not pulling the trigger on Nd5 or exf5), I played for an attack, but never burned my bridges and instead focused on central control, and I kept queens on the board until it was winning to trade. Now if only I didn't miss a few easy checks to regain my rook during the endgame... } { [%clk 0:00:16] } 0-1


