lthough I felt that I would be fine here as soon as my knight reaches b4. } 19. Qc3! $14 { Stockfish's amazing recommendation stops the Na6-b4 maneuver and thereby gets the slightest of advantages in an otherwise equal position. Did not see this move in the game. }) 17... Qe7 { [%clk 0:01:40] } 18. Ne4 { [%clk 0:02:42] } 18... Na6 { [%clk 0:01:32] } 19. Qc4 { [%clk 0:02:42] } 19... Nb4 { [%clk 0:01:29] } 20. Rac1 $10 { With my dream setup achieved, I estimated (correctly!) that this position was perfectly equal. } { [%clk 0:02:37] } 20... Rac8 { [%clk 0:01:28] } 21. Nxd6 { [%clk 0:02:28] } 21... Qxd6 { [%clk 0:01:30] } 22. Qc5 { And with the queens coming off, it's now painfully obvious that white has nothing anymore. I'm very pleased with how I navigated the subtleties of this new variation, knowing no theory and only key ideas. } { [%clk 0:02:29] } (22. e4 Rfd8 23. b3 c5 24. dxc5 Qxd1+ 25. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 26. Bf1 $10) 22... Qxc5 { [%clk 0:01:23] } 23. Rxc5 { [%clk 0:02:30] } (23. dxc5? Rfd8 $15) 23... b6 { [%clk 0:01:20] } 24. Rcc1 { The c6 pawn is not a weakness due to the powerhorse (pun intended) on b4. Moreover, c5 is hard to stop. } { [%cal Gb4c6] [%clk 0:02:26] } 24... Rfd8 { [%clk 0:01:21] } 25. e3 { [%clk 0:02:26] } 25... Kf8 { [%clk 0:01:16] } 26. Kf1 { [%clk 0:02:27] } 26... Ke7 { [%clk 0:01:17] } 27. Ke2 { [%clk 0:02:28] } 27... c5! { [%clk 0:00:53] } 28. dxc5 { [%clk 0:02:22] } 28... Rxd1 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 29. Kxd1 { [%clk 0:02:16] } (29. Rxd1 Rxc5 $10 { An easy equality for black. With Rc2 coming, white has nothing. }) 29... bxc5?! { [%clk 0:00:53] } (29... Nd3! { A missed opportunity that Jesse immediately mentioned on stream after I made my move. } 30. Rc2 { [%cal Gc2f2,Gc2b2] } 30... Rxc5! $17 { [%cal Gd3f2,Gd3b2] }) 30. Ke2?! { [%clk 0:02:14] } (30. Bf1! { Stopping c4 ensures that my c pawn is not a strength, but a potential liability. Moreover, this stops the Nd3 move that crushed him last move. } { [%csl Gc4,Gd3] }) 30... c4 { [%clk 0:00:44] } 31. Rc3 { [%clk 0:02:08] } 31... Na2 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 32. Rc2 { [%clk 0:02:07] } 32... Nb4 { Always repeat. } { [%clk 0:00:41] } 33. Rc3 { [%clk 0:02:01] } 33... Na2 { [%clk 0:00:41] } (33... Kd6! { The move you want to play. I couldn't justify it during the game because I didn't see the correct continuation: } 34. b3 Na2! 35. Rxc4 Rxc4 36. bxc4 Nc3+ { [%csl Ga4] } 37. Kd3 Nxa4 $17 { [%cal Ga5a1,Gd6c5] }) 34. Ra3? { [%clk 0:02:00] } (34. Rc2 Kd6 { I probably would have played this seeing as the following line shows b3 is not possible: } 35. b3?? c3 { [%cal Ga2b4] } 36. Rxa2?? c2 $19 { [%cal Gc2c1] }) 34... c3? { I didn't believe I was better, so found a nice idea to liquidate into a clearly drawn endgame. } { [%clk 0:00:29] } (34... Nc1+!! 35. Kd2 Nd3! $17 { Tricky knight maneuvers. Black remains fully in control, and the knight is clearly much better than this clown on g2 hitting nothing. } { [%cal Gd3f2,Gd3b2] }) 35. bxc3 { [%clk 0:01:53] } (35. Rxa2?? c2 $19 { [%cal Gc2c1] }) 35... Nxc3+ { [%clk 0:00:30] } 36. Kd3 { [%clk 0:01:43] } 36... Nd1 { [%clk 0:00:27] } 37. Ra2! { The only move. White secures the 2nd rank and "traps" the knight on d1. } { [%clk 0:01:06] } 37... Rd8+ { [%clk 0:00:18] } (37... Nc3?? 38. Rc2 $18) 38. Kc4 { [%clk 0:01:07] } 38... Rb8 { Cutting off the king and giving my knight a possible escape. If the king retreated, I wasn't quite yet sure I had a way to make further progress or if I'd have to repeat as well. } { [%csl Gb3,Gb4,Gb5][%cal Gd1b2,Gb8b1] [%clk 0:00:10] } 39. Bc6 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 39... Rb4+ { [%clk 0:00:08] } 40. Kc5 { [%clk 0:00:50] } 40... Nc3 { [%clk 0:00:08] } 41. Ra3 { [%clk 0:00:41] } 41... Nd1 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 42. Bb5! { Going for the win! I knew I had to be fine here, but it's still quite tough to handle this soon-to-be passed a pawn. } { [%clk 0:00:37] } (42. Ra2 { I again thought this would lead to a draw - I had yet to see Jesse's idea. } 42... Nc3 $10) 42... Nxf2 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 43. Kb6 { [%clk 0:00:38] } 43... Ne4 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 44. Kxa5 { [%clk 0:00:39] } 44... Rb2 { [%clk 0:00:06] } 45. Kb6 { [%clk 0:00:36] } 45... Rxh2 { [%clk 0:00:06] } (45... Nd6 $10 { The safe move - stopping the further advance of the a pawn. }) 46. a5 { [%clk 0:00:37] } 46... Rb2 { [%clk 0:00:05] } 47. a6!! { [%clk 0:00:21] } 47... Nd6 { Which phrase trumps the other: "pin and win" or "rooks belong behind passed pawns"? } { [%cal Gd6b5,Gb2b5] [%clk 0:00:05] } 48. a7 { [%clk 0:00:22] } 48... Nxb5 { [%clk 0:00:04] } 49. a8=Q { [%clk 0:00:12] } 49... Nc7+?? { Such a travesty. I hallucinated that Kxc7 was impossible, and thought I was simply regaining the pawn and entering a winning rook and pawn endgame... } { [%cal Gb6c7] [%clk 0:00:06] } (49... Nxa3+! 50. Kc7 Nb5+ 51. Kc6 Nd6 $10 { A very tough position to play for both sides. I'm still reasonably sure I would prefer white here even if I had seen this as the best line. None of my pieces have defended outposts! } { [%cal Gb2b7,Gg7g6,Gh6h5] }) 50. Kxc7 { 1-0 White wins. } { [%clk 0:00:12] } (50. Kc6?? Nxa8 51. Rxa8 Rb3 $19 { My hallucination. Black should have an easy time converting here. }) 1-0


