1. d4 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 2. c4 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 2... e6 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 3. Nf3 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 3... d5 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 4. Nc3 { [%clk 0:02:49] } 4... c6 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 5. Bg5 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 5... dxc4 { [%clk 0:02:58] } 6. e4 { [%clk 0:02:47] } 6... b5 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 7. e5 { [%clk 0:02:48] } 7... h6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 8. Bh4 { [%clk 0:02:49] } 8... g5 { [%clk 0:03:01] } 9. Nxg5 { [%clk 0:02:50] } 9... hxg5 { [%clk 0:03:03] } 10. Bxg5 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 10... Nbd7 { [%clk 0:03:04] } 11. g3 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 11... Bb7 { [%clk 0:02:59] } 12. Bg2 { [%clk 0:02:52] } 12... Qb6 { [%clk 0:03:00] } 13. exf6 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 13... c5 { [%clk 0:02:58] } 14. d5 { [%clk 0:02:53] } 14... O-O-O { [%clk 0:02:48] } 15. O-O { [%clk 0:02:42] } 15... b4 { All mainline Botvinnik theory } { [%clk 0:02:47] } 16. Na4 { [%clk 0:02:43] } 16... Qb5 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 17. a3 { [%clk 0:02:42] } 17... Kb8?? { With one terrible move I completely throw away the game. } { [%clk 0:01:35] } (17... Nb8! { The theoretical move that I really should have remembered... } 18. axb4 cxb4 19. Qg4 Bxd5 20. Rfc1 Nc6 21. Bxd5 Rxd5 22. Rxc4 Rxg5 23. Qd4 Kb8 24. Rxc6 Rxg3+ 25. fxg3 { Kramnik, Vladimir - Anand, V., 1/2-1/2, 6th London Classic 2014, https://lichess.org/fidio1sX } 25... Qxc6 $10) 18. dxe6 { [%clk 0:02:36] } 18... Bxg2 { [%clk 0:01:31] } 19. e7 { With the king on c8, the rook on d8 is defended, so I could play Bxf1 here. } { [%clk 0:02:30] } 19... Rc8 { [%clk 0:01:25] } 20. Kxg2 { [%clk 0:02:28] } 20... Bh6 { [%clk 0:01:11] } 21. h4! { If I ever take the bishop on g5, the g5-f6-e7 pawn chain would just crush me. } { [%clk 0:02:09] } 21... Qc6+ { [%clk 0:01:03] } 22. f3?! { [%clk 0:02:06] } (22. Qf3! $18 { Practically speaking, after this move, I'm completely dead. White's pawns dominate the board, so there's no longer a need to prolong the opposite-sides castling fight. }) 22... Nxf6! { Chipping away at the pawn chain, and bringing the knight into the attack... } { [%clk 0:00:57] } 23. axb4?! { [%clk 0:02:02] } (23. Bxf6 Qxf6 $18 { Once again, a cleaner way forward for white. }) 23... Bxg5! { [%clk 0:00:48] } 24. hxg5 { [%clk 0:01:49] } 24... Ng4! { I'm still 100% lost, but now there is only one road to victory for white. } { [%clk 0:00:49] } 25. Qe1?? { The third-best move is completely lost for white! } { [%clk 0:01:47] } (25. Qc1!! { Having Qf4+ is a crucial resource that white needs. } 25... Rh2+ 26. Kg1 Rch8 27. Qf4+! Ka8 28. Qxg4 $18) (25. Re1? { The second-best move requires inhuman accuracy to reach a draw. } 25... Rh2+ 26. Kg1 Qc7! { [%cal Gc7g3] } 27. f4 Qc6! 28. Re4! Qxe4 29. Qd6+ Rc7 30. Qd8+ Rc8 31. Qd6+ Rc7 32. Qd8+ (32. e8=Q+?? Qxe8 $19) 32... Rc8 33. Qd6+ $10) 25... Rh2+ { [%clk 0:00:26] } 26. Kg1 { [%clk 0:01:47] } 26... Rch8 { Hilariously, white cannot stop the threat of Rh1+ and R1h2# except by giving up the kitchen sink. } { [%clk 0:00:21] } 27. e8=Q+ { [%clk 0:01:35] } (27. fxg4?? Qh1#) 27... Rxe8 { [%clk 0:00:21] } 28. Qc1 { [%clk 0:01:30] } 28... Re3! { Stops Qf4+ and prepares Rxf3, finally crashing through. Every piece remains untouchable. } { [%clk 0:00:06] } (28... Ree2! 29. Qf4+ Ne5! { I didn't see this move. Once again, the two rook checkmate is unstoppable. }) 29. Qxc4 { [%clk 0:01:19] } (29. fxg4?? Qg2#) 29... Rxf3? { [%clk 0:00:04] } (29... Rh1+!! 30. Kxh1 Rxf3 { The correct way to handle this. The rook is untouchable here, and you can't stop Rxf1 double check! } 31. Qf4+ (31. Rxf3 Qxf3+ 32. Kg1 Qf2+ 33. Kh1 Qh2#) (31. Kg2 Rxf1+ 32. Kxf1 Qf3+ 33. Ke1 Qf2+ 34. Kd1 Ne3+ 35. Kc1 Qe1#) 31... Rxf4+ 32. Kg1 Ne3 $19 { [%cal Gc6g2] }) 30. Qxg4?? { I believe Andras thought this move came with check. My Kb8 blunder earlier in the game finally shows its usefulness! } { [%clk 0:01:18] } (30. Rxf3! Rh1+ (30... Qxf3?? 31. Qb5+ $18) 31. Kg2! Ne3+ 32. Kf2 Nxc4 33. Rxh1 Ne5 { And black has to win the game all over again! }) 30... Rxf1+ { [%clk 0:00:03] } 31. Kxf1 { [%clk 0:00:58] } 31... Qg2+ { [%clk 0:00:04] } (31... Qh1# { A faster mate... }) 32. Ke1 { [%clk 0:00:57] } 32... Qf2+ { [%clk 0:00:05] } 33. Kd1 { [%clk 0:00:55] } 33... Qd2# { 0-1 Black wins by checkmate. } { [%clk 0:00:05] } 0-1


